10 different types of lock

What I did:
I observed different types of locks used around my accommodation, campus, and everyday life. I also considered digital locks used on personal devices. I collected examples and took photos where possible.

What I found:
1.	Keycard lock – used for my room at UniHall. The door only unlocks when a valid card is scanned.
2.	Elevator access control lock – requires a keycard to activate the elevator, restricting access to certain floors.
3.	Padlock – commonly used to secure bicycles or lockers using a physical key.
4.	Combination lock – used in gym lockers, where a correct number sequence is required to unlock.
5.	Deadbolt lock – a traditional door lock that provides strong physical security using a key.	
6.	Magnetic lock (maglock) – used in some building entrances, where the door remains locked until access is granted electronically.
7.	Cam lock – used in cabinets or drawers to secure personal items.
8.	Turnstile gate – used to control entry into restricted areas by allowing only one person through at a time.
9.	Fingerprint lock – uses fingerprint recognition to authenticate the user before granting access, commonly used in smartphones or secure systems.
10.	Facial recognition lock /FaceID – uses facial recognition technology to verify identity and unlock devices.

These locks demonstrate different methods of access control and authentication in both physical and digital environments. Traditional locks rely on physical keys or codes, while modern systems use electronic and biometric methods. Biometric locks provide stronger security because they are based on unique personal characteristics. Together, these systems help prevent unauthorized access and protect assets.
